'''Oomahiko Shrine''' (おおまひこじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Myōjin-chō (Tokushima)|Q11512591|WD=Q11512591|lt=Myōjin-chō|1=Myōjin-chō}}, {{ill|lt=Tokushima|Q207309|WD=Q207309|1=Tokushima (city)}}, {{ill|lt=Tokushima Prefecture|Q160734|WD=Q160734|1=Tokushima Prefecture}}. It is written the same as {{ill|lt=Ōasahiko Shrine|Q723417|WD=Q723417|1=Ōasahiko Shrine}}, enshrined in {{ill|lt=Naruto|Q460812|WD=Q460812|1=Naruto, Tokushima}}, but read differently.

=== History ===
It is said that Kōno Yakichirō, son of a retainer who moved from Kōno-no-shō in {{ill|lt=Iyo Province|Q907829|WD=Q907829|1=Iyo Province}} to {{ill|lt=Awa Province|Q907457|WD=Q907457|1=Awa Province (Tokushima)}} and served the {{ill|lt=Hachisuka clan|Q2975261|WD=Q2975261|1=Hachisuka clan}}, welcomed the {{ill|lt=shintai|Q327532|WD=Q327532|1=Shintai}} of Ōmahiko Shrine from Ichinomiya in {{ill|lt=Myōdō District|Q1156486|WD=Q1156486|1=Myōdō District, Tokushima}} in {{ill|lt=1653|Q6965|WD=Q6965|1=1653}} ({{ill|lt=Jōō|Q1145081|WD=Q1145081|1=Jōō (Edo period)}} 2), making it the guardian shrine of the Kōno family. There is also a theory identifying it with the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} "Manotohiko Shrine" listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}. It was originally called Yakichi Myōjin, but in {{ill|lt=1870|Q7741|WD=Q7741|1=1870}} (Meiji 3) the name was changed to the current one, and it was listed as a {{ill|lt=Sonsha|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

